Project 2, Part1, F1 Material Transportation with Minimum Cost Flow Problem¶

Author: Alejo González García¶

For this project, let´s say we are the FIA, Federation Internationale de l'Automobile. In Formula 1, each year, many countries around the world are visited. For our problem we are going to visit 15 cities in most of the continents.

The problem we have to solve consists in satisfying the demand on each race week but trying to minimize the cost. Each of the paths that we have, have an associated cost that measures all the money we have to spend if we use that path in 100$ per ton of cargo. We want to satisfy all the demand but making sure to use the most optimal path. Remark that we do not need to use the full a capacity of a link, we have the maximum tons we can send and the money that each of those tons costs.

In order to reduce costs, the FIA, has located it´s production factories in just a few cities around the world (Montreal, São Paulo, Singapore and Vegas). This cities are going to be shown in the graph as the ones with positive demand in blue color. The cities that do not produce materials, but need them, will be shown in red color with a negative demand.

We assume the productor cities satisfy their own demand and the transportation cost is null.

Probably you have noticed that we have defined the links between the cities by using directly the name of the two cities involved. It is a requirement that we can go from that text to an interpretable approach that pyomo can understant to solve the problem. We are going to define a matrix that contains as many rows as nodes, cities and as many columns as arcs. The value will be 0 if no connection, 1 if that is the initial node in that arc and -1 if that is the final node in that arc.

In [ ]:
# Create a matrix filled with zeros
matrix = np.zeros((len(nodes), len(arcs)), dtype=int) # matrix size is nodes * arcs

# Populate the matrix based on arcs
for j, arc in enumerate(arcs):
    initial_node, final_node = arc
    initial_index = nodes.index(initial_node)
    final_index = nodes.index(final_node)
    matrix[initial_index, j] = 1
    matrix[final_index, j] = -1

print(matrix)

Model Definition¶

\begin{align*} & \text{Sets:} & & \text{{Nodes}} = \{\text{{Vegas, Miami, Jeddah, Melbourne, Baku, San Petersburgh, São Paulo, Valencia, Singapore, Montreal, Imola, Silverstone, China, Mexico, Abu Dhabi}}\} \\ & & & \text{{Arcs}} = \{0, 1, 2, \ldots, n-1\}, \quad n \in \text{{number of connections}} \\ & \\ & \text{Variables:} & & x_{i} \geq 0, \quad \forall i \in \text{Arcs} \\ & & & \text{where } x_{i} \text{ represents the amount of tons sent on arc } i \\ & & & \text{with } x \in \mathbb{R}^{\geq 0} \\ & \\ & \text{Objective Function:} & & \min \sum_{j \in \text{{Arcs}}} \text{{Cost}}_j \cdot x_j \quad \text{for } j \in \text{{Arcs}} \\ & \\ & & &\text{subject to}\\ & \text{Constraints: } & & \quad x_j \leq \text{{Capacity}}_j \quad \text{for } j \in \text{{Arcs}} \\ & & & \sum_{j \in \text{{Arcs}}} x_j \cdot \text{{matrix}}[i][j] \text{= Demand[i]} \quad \text{where } i \in \text{{Nodes}}, j \in \text{{Arcs}} \end{align*}

Notice that in the Node we will use a transformation to return just the index of each city.

  • The amount of cargo sent on each link cannot be larger than the link capacity.
  • The demand of each node must be satisfied. The sum of ingoing and outgoing cargo must be equal to the demand of that city.
In [ ]:
model = ConcreteModel("F1_Network_Optimization")

# Define sets
model.Nodes = Set(initialize=nodes)
model.Arcs = Set(initialize=range(len(arcs)))

# Parameters
model.Cost = Param(model.Arcs, initialize = cost_dollars, doc = "Cost in 100$ per ton of cargo.")
model.Capacity = Param(model.Arcs, initialize = capacities, doc = "Maximum amount of tons that a link can take.")
model.Demand = Param(model.Arcs, initialize = demand, doc = "Demand of each city.")

# Decision variables
model.x = Var(model.Arcs, domain=NonNegativeReals, doc='Amount of Tons I send on each arc')

# Objective function
model.objective = Objective(
    expr=sum(model.Cost[j] * model.x[j] for j in model.Arcs), sense=minimize,  doc='Minimize the cost of transportation')

# Capacity constraint
def capacity_rule(model, j):
    return model.x[j] <= model.Capacity[j]

model.Maximum_Capacity = Constraint(model.Arcs, rule=capacity_rule)

# Demand satisfaction constraint
def demand_satisfied(model, node):
    demand_index = nodes.index(node)
    inflow = sum(model.x[j] for j in model.Arcs if matrix[demand_index][j] == 1) # making sure inflow of a city is correct
    outflow = sum(model.x[j] for j in model.Arcs if matrix[demand_index][j] == -1) # making sure outflow of a city is correct
    return (inflow - outflow) == model.Demand[demand_index]

model.Demand_Satisfied = Constraint(model.Nodes, rule=demand_satisfied)
# This constraint is the one that forces the model to get each city with its corresponding demand satisfied.

Now we are going to solve the model and make sure that the problem is feasible and has a solution:

In [ ]:
# Solve the model
# solver = SolverFactory('glpk')
solver = SolverFactory('gurobi')

result = solver.solve(model, tee=True)

# Check solver status
if result.solver.status == SolverStatus.ok and result.solver.termination_condition == TerminationCondition.optimal:
    print(f"\nTotal Cost: {model.objective()}")
else:
    print("Solver did not converge to an optimal solution. Check the model and constraints.")
    # You can print additional information about the solver status if needed
    print(result.solver)

Project 2, Part2, Formula 1 Aerodynamics Optimization¶

In Formula 1, optimizing aerodynamics is crucial for achieving high performance. Let's consider a 3D objective function aimed at minimizing the aerodynamic drag force on a Formula 1 car. The objective function takes into account the car's speed, the angle of attack, and the air density.

The aerodynamic drag force is given by the equation:

\begin{align*} F_{\text{drag}} = \frac{1}{2} \rho v^2 C_d A \end{align*}

Where: \begin{align*} \rho & : \text{Air density (kg/m}^3\text{)} \\ v & : \text{flow velocity (km/h)} \\ C_d & : \text{Drag coefficient (nonlinear, dependent on \(\alpha\))} \\ A & : \text{Frontal area of the car (m}^2\text{)} \end{align*}

The drag coefficient is assumed to be nonlinear and dependent on the angle of attack, alpha:

\begin{align*} C_d = 0.1 + 0.01 \alpha^2 \end{align*}

The angle of attack (alpha) for an Formula 1 car can vary depending on the design, aerodynamic philosophy, and specific conditions. However:

Negative Values (Downforce): Formula 1 cars are designed to generate downforce to improve grip on the track. Negative alpha (where the front wing is angled downward and the rear wing is angled upward) helps generate downforce. Typical values for negative alpha range from -5 degrees to -2 degrees.

Positive Values (Top Speed): In some situations, teams might adjust the alpha to reduce drag and maximize top speed. Positive alpha (front wing angled slightly upward, rear wing angled downward) can help decrease downforce and aerodynamic drag on straight portions of the track. Positive values may range from 1 to 3 degrees.

It's important to note that these values can vary significantly between teams and even between different tracks. Teams optimize the aerodynamics based on the characteristics of each circuit, considering the balance between downforce and drag for optimal performance.

During this practice, we are going to try to optimize the drag force for the most extreme case, where we want to have the minimum possible drag.

Defining the variables thresholds:

In [ ]:
min_speed = 280
max_speed = 325

min_alpha = -5
max_alpha = 3

min_rho = 1.2
max_rho = 1.65

min_area = 1.7
max_area = 2.5

Defining the functions we are going to use:

In [ ]:
# Fix values for rho and area at their average minimum values
avg_min_rho = (min_rho + max_rho) / 2 ; print("Average rho:",avg_min_rho)
avg_min_area = (min_area + max_area) / 2  ; print("Average area:",avg_min_area)

def drag_coeff(alpha):
    Cd = 0.1 + 0.01 * alpha**2
    return Cd

# Function to calculate the objective value (aerodynamic drag force)
def aerodynamic_drag(v, alpha, rho, A):
    Cd = drag_coeff(alpha)
    # Aerodynamic drag force formula
    F_drag = 0.5 * rho * v**2 * Cd * A
    return F_drag

Average rho: 1.4249999999999998
Average area: 2.1

Model Definition¶

\begin{align} \text{Minimize:} & \quad F_{\text{drag}} = \frac{1}{2} \rho v^2 C_d A \\ \end{align}

\begin{align*} \text{Where:} & \\ \rho & : \text{Air density (kg/m}^3\text{)} \\ v & : \text{flow velocity (km/h)} \\ C_d & : \text{Drag coefficient (nonlinear, dependent on \(\alpha\))} \\ A & : \text{Frontal area of the car (m}^2\text{)} \end{align*}

\begin{align*} \text{Subject to:} & \\ & \quad \text{Air-Area Flow Constraint:} \quad car speed \leq \text{100 * (rho * area)}\\ & \quad \text{Car Speed Constraint:} \quad \text{Air Flow Velocity} \geq 280, \quad \text{Air Flow Velocity} \leq 325 \\ & \quad \text{Angle of Attack Constraint:} \quad -5 \leq \text{alpha} \leq 3\\ & \quad \text{Air Density Constraint:} \quad 1.2 \leq \text{rho} \leq 1.65\\ & \quad \text{Front Area Constraint:} \quad 1.7 \leq \text{area} \leq 2.5\\ \end{align*}

  • Air-Area relation must be seriously taken into account. If this value exceeds is just 1% the speed of the car, we enter into the danger zone where turbulent air could be produced and the pilot could lose control.
  • Speed of the car must be bounded to the circuit capabilities. As we are focusing on the straights, speed will be on the range 280 to 325 kilometers per hour.
  • Angle of attack is the inclination of the car as we explained above.
  • Air density will depend on the part of the circuit in which we are.
  • The front area is a parameter that can be adjusted by replacing the front wing to another one. That is why we have different possible areas.
In [ ]:
# Create a Pyomo concrete model
model2 = ConcreteModel("Drag Force Optimization")

# Variables
model2.car_speed = Var(within=NonNegativeReals, doc = "air flow due to car speed (km/h)")
model2.alpha = Var(within=Reals, doc = "angle of attack (degrees)") 
model2.rho = Var(within=NonNegativeReals, doc = "Air density (kg/m^3)") 
model2.area = Var(within=NonNegativeReals, doc = "Frontal area of the car (m^2)") 

# Objective function with multiple components
model2.obj = Objective(expr=aerodynamic_drag(model2.car_speed, model2.alpha, model2.rho, model2.area),
                       doc = "Minimize the Aerodynamic Drag", sense=minimize)

# Constraints: 

# Air-Flow security limitation (turbulent air)
def area_air_flow_constraint(car_speed, rho, area):
    return (car_speed) <= 100 * (rho * area)
model2.area_air_flow = Constraint(expr=area_air_flow_constraint(model2.car_speed, model2.rho, model2.area), doc="Maximum Speed Air Flow")

# Angle of attack bounds
model2.alpha_lower_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.alpha >= min_alpha, doc = "Minimum Allowed Angle Of Attack")
model2.alpha_upper_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.alpha <= max_alpha, doc = "Maximum Allowed Angle Of Attack")

# Bounds for the Rho, the air density. 
model2.rho_lower_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.rho >= min_rho, doc = "Minimum Allowed Air density")
model2.rho_upper_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.rho <= max_rho, doc = "Maximum Allowed Air density")

# Speed bounds
model2.speed_lower_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.car_speed >= min_speed, doc = "Minimum Allowed Speed")
model2.speed_upper_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.car_speed <= max_speed, doc = "Maximum Allowed Speed")

# Bounds for the area of the front of the car
model2.area_lower_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.area >= min_area, doc = "Minimum Allowed Area")
model2.area_upper_bound = Constraint(expr=model2.area <= max_area, doc = "Maximum Allowed Area")

We should notice that for this equation, the velocity is quadratic and so is the angle of attack. As we are going to multiply 2 quadratic terms, our function is going to be in 4 dimensions. This means that we cannot apply conventional solvers, we can use one of the best ones for non linear cases that is ipopt.

contour = plt.contourf(alpha_mesh, speed_mesh, drag_values, levels=30, cmap='cool')  # Swap x-axis and y-axis
plt.colorbar(contour, label='Aerodynamic Drag')

# Scatter plot for the optimal point
plt.scatter(optimal_alpha, optimal_speed, color='red', marker='x', label='Optimal Point', s=100)

plt.xlabel('Angle of Attack (degrees)')
plt.ylabel('Car Speed (km/h)')  # Swap x-axis and y-axis
plt.title('Rotated Contour Plot of Aerodynamic Drag with Optimal Point')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

As in the previous plot, this is just a 2D visualization that corroborates the previous data, the lowest point is selected.

Now we are going to check for the values between the Area of the front of the car and the Air density:

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Define the range of air density and area values
rho_values = np.linspace(min_rho, max_rho, 100)
area_values = np.linspace(min_area, max_area, 100)

# Create 2D meshgrid
Rho, Area = np.meshgrid(rho_values, area_values, indexing='ij')

# Calculate aerodynamic drag force for each data point
drag_values = aerodynamic_drag(optimal_speed, optimal_alpha, Rho, Area)

# Plotting with legend
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
contour = plt.contourf(Area, Rho, drag_values, levels=30, cmap='cool')
plt.colorbar(contour, label='Aerodynamic Drag')

# Scatter plot for the optimal point
plt.scatter(optimal_area, optimal_rho, color='red', marker='x', label='Optimal Point', s=100)

plt.xlabel('Frontal Area of the Car (m^2)')
plt.ylabel('Air Density (kg/m^3)')
plt.title('Contour Plot of Aerodynamic Drag with Optimal Point')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

We can see that due to our Air-Area flow constraint, an optimal solution is chosen that is not that obvious. This is due to the fact that the speed of the car should not be larger than the product of the air flow and the area, due to the fact that we could have turbulent air. A medium sized wing should be selected for the car together with a middle height circuit where the air density is medium (1.38 kg/m^3).

We can also compare the air density with the car speed in a 2D plot, but the answer is obvious:

Here we can see that the minimum speed is selected in order to minimize the drag, while the air density is not. This is due to the Air-Area constraint that we have.

Finally, let´s plot a 3D version of our problem, but now focusing on the air and area together with the speed:

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# Define the range of air density, car speed, and frontal area values
rho_values = np.linspace(min_rho, max_rho, 100)
speed_values = np.linspace(min_speed, max_speed, 100)
area_values = np.linspace(min_area, max_area, 100)

# Create 3D meshgrid
Rho, Speed, Area = np.meshgrid(rho_values, speed_values, area_values, indexing='ij')

# Calculate aerodynamic drag force for each data point
drag_values = aerodynamic_drag(Speed, optimal_alpha, Rho, Area)

# Plotting with legend
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
surface = ax.scatter3D(Speed.flatten(), Rho.flatten(), Area.flatten(), c=drag_values.flatten(), cmap='cool', marker='o')

# Scatter plot for the optimal point
ax.scatter(optimal_speed, optimal_rho, optimal_area, color='red', marker='x', s=100, label='Optimal Point')

ax.set_xlabel('Car Speed (km/h)')
ax.set_ylabel('Air Density (kg/m^3)')
ax.set_zlabel('Frontal Area (m^2)')
ax.set_title('3D Plot of Aerodynamic Drag with Optimal Point')

# Add colorbar and legend
cbar = fig.colorbar(surface, ax=ax, pad=0.1, aspect=10)
cbar.set_label('Aerodynamic Drag Force')
cbar.ax.get_yaxis().labelpad = 15  # Adjust padding for the colorbar label

plt.legend()
plt.show()

Here we can see that the minimum drag force is found in the blue part, where the speed is minimum, the air density and the frontal area too. Notice that this is what our model has taken into account to provide the solution.

So finally, we can see that the obtained values in order to minimize the drag force are to reduce all the parameters. There is an exception related to the Air-Area maximum flow, that as we explained does not allow the cars to increase this treshold for security reasons as turbulent air could be produced.
